Lets explain the dataset first.

A data frame with 234 rows and 11 variables:

Variables Information:

manufacturer: manufacturer name

model:model name

displ:engine displacement, in litres

year:year of manufacture

cyl:number of cylinders

trans:type of transmission

drv: the type of drive train, where f = front-wheel drive, r = rear wheel drive, 4 = 4wd

cty: city miles per gallon

hwy: highway miles per gallon

fl: fuel type

class: type of car

Lets talk a bit about ggplot2 library and see some basic operations.

ggplot(mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = class, y = drv))

ggplot(mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color= displ))

ggplot(mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color= displ<5)) 

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = "blue")

Help Function and facet functions.

  • Help function is to view documentation on a given function or library and even on sample datasets included with R like the one we are using in this excercise.
  • Facets are used to display categorical variables.

There are two types of facet functions available i.e.facet_wrap() and facet_grid()

?ggplot2 #help function

#to facet your plot by a single variable, use facet_wrap()

#facet_wrap - to be applied only on discrete(integers or whole numbers) variables.
ggplot(mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~class, nrow = 2)

To Facet on two variables:

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

If you prefer to not facet in the rows or columns dimension, use a . instead of a variable name, e.g.+ facet_grid(. ~ cyl).

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x= displ, y= hwy), color = "blue") +
  facet_grid(.~cyl)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = drv, y = cyl))

We can deduce a few things from above plot, i.e 4wd vehicles usually come up with 4,6,8 cylinders and front-wheel drive vehicles have 4,5,6 and 8 cylinders as well, however, rear-wheel drive vehicles only have 6 or 8 cylinder options.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

geom_smooth(): has extra aesthetics named as linetype, and group. you will see below. geom_smooth() will draw a different line, with a different linetype, for each unique value of the variable that you map to linetype.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, linetype = drv))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Lets begin some fun.

Multiple Geoms

Things to remember: - either give joint color to ggplot instead of separate geoms, or in a way given below by passing it as aesthetics in geom_smooth.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(mapping =aes(linetype = drv, color = drv) )
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

If you want to remove the legend: use show.legend = FALSE

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, group = drv, color = drv), show.legend = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Filter function - suppose you want to create a scatterplot to show how much a vehicle can cover based on its class and compare with a particular class say, subcompact. we can use a combination of geoms to showcase this scenario.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(data = filter(mpg, class == 'subcompact'), se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Other Geoms

Type of Plot Geom Function Description
Point geom_point() Scatter plot.
Point geom_jitter() Scatter plot with jitter (random noise to each point).
Line geom_line() Line plot.
Line geom_step() Step plot.
Bar geom_bar() Bar plot.
Bar geom_col() Column plot (similar to bar plot).
Area geom_area() Area plot.
Boxplot geom_boxplot() Boxplot.
Smooth geom_smooth() Adds a smoothed line to the plot.
Tile geom_tile() Tile plot.
Polygon geom_polygon() Polygon plot.
Histogram geom_histogram() Histogram.
Density geom_density() Density plot.
Errorbar geom_errorbar() Error bar plot.
Text geom_text() Adds text labels to the plot.

Feel free to explore them before going forward

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

To remove confidence envelope around the regression lines, use se = FALSE, in geom_smooth()

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Total number of models in a particular class i.e.compact, midsize or suv and so-on

model_class <- mpg %>%
  group_by(class) %>%
  summarise(model_count = n(), .groups = 'drop')
model_class %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= class, y = model_count, fill = class)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', position = 'dodge') +
  labs(title = "Number of models in a particular class",
       x = 'Class',
       y = 'Model_count') +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 10)

Similarly, lets find out total number of models by a particular manufacturer.

man_model <- mpg %>%
  group_by(manufacturer) %>%
  summarise(model_count = n(), .groups = 'drop')
man_model %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= manufacturer, y = model_count)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', position = 'dodge') +
  geom_text(aes(label = model_count), vjust = -0.2) + 
  labs(title = "Total models of a manufacturer",
       x = 'Manufacturer',
       y = 'Model_count') +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 10)

** Find out total number of models by a given manufacturer in a particular class.

year_model <- mpg %>%
  group_by(manufacturer,class) %>%
  summarise(model_count = n(), .groups = 'drop')
